	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Espozo wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">no matter how much extra processing power you give a system, it will always be dragged down by it's video hardware</div><br />Raw graphics processing power isn't quite so important so long as video bandwidth into the machine is sufficient. And on NES, Neo Geo, and any handheld with a TV tuner cartridge (Game Gear, TurboExpress, Game Boy Advance), there's essentially as much video bandwidth as you'd possibly need. Super NES not so much, but it is enough to push a coprocessor-rendered 160x144x2bpp viewport to VRAM at 60 fps in Super Game Boy or a larger viewport at a slower rate in Super FX games.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


