	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The Super Gameboy didn't actually render sprites or anything? Also, since I'm not too familiar with all these &quot;fancy&quot; terms like video bandwidth, does that what effects things like how much data you can DMA to VRAM? I remember that it has been discussed that the SNES can update 3 64x64 sprites under absolutely perfect conditions. Just thinking about it, I heard that 256x240 mode isn't very good because it takes a large amount of time away form things like updating VRAM so I got to wondering. Couldn't you actually get more time if you disable rendering for a bit and turn it back on (obviously) latter? How much time do you lose doing 256x240 mode, because if you made the display 208 pixels tall, shouldn't you gain twice as much time as you lost if the display was 240 pixels tall? Sorry if this doesn't make any sense...

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Sat Feb 07, 2015 5:23 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Sega Genesis + 32X vs SNES + SD2SNES</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />You're correct in guessing that &quot;video memory bandwidth&quot; refers to how much data can be copied to VRAM per second or per frame. There are 341 dots in a scanline, 10 of which are reserved for WRAM refreshing. It takes the DMA unit two dots to copy one byte. Thus 262 total lines - 224 picture lines = 38 blanking lines, and 38 blanking lines * 331 dots/line / 2 dots/byte = 6289 bytes. Practically, you can probably do 6 KiB (6144 bytes). (I might be missing something related to time taken to load sprites that are displayed on the first line.) Calculations for 239, 208, and 192 lines are an exercise for the reader.<br /><br />Super Game Boy contains a coprocessor consisting of the Game Boy SoC with some glue logic to buffer scanlines on their way to the Super NES. 160x144 pixels at 2bpp is 160*144*2/8 = 5760 bytes, which comes in just under the roughly 6 KiB per frame limit for 224-line mode. Adding a full OAM DMA would appear to put it over the limit, but perhaps it performs only a partial OAM DMA. Someone who has disassembled the SGB BIOS would be able to tell you more.<br /><br />Super FX games tend to be letterboxed to allow for more bandwidth. For example, <em>Star Fox</em> is 224x192.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


