	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Sega Genesis + 32X vs SNES + SD2SNES</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />In other words, the &quot;Xbox piped into a TV tuner&quot; solution. Video memory bandwidth would be the limiting factor there.<br /><br />On the other hand, newer games are framed for 16:9. You could have the game render to 256x176 and letterbox the crap out of it. This gives (262-176)*331/2 = over 14000 bytes per frame. At 4bpp, the entire frame is 256*176*4/8=22528 bytes, enough to double buffer a whole 4bpp plane at 30 fps. Dither everything down to <a href="http://www.pixeljoint.com/forum/forum_posts.asp?TID=12795" class="postlink">Dawnbringer's palette</a> and enjoy &quot;state-of-the-art high-resolution graphics&quot;.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


